Data Description:¶

This data has 55 columns and 10,000 contining the credit and demographic information of its customers. There are 10 columns with null values from ranging 24 to 8500.¶

This dataset also 13 'object' columns which are categorical along with a few other categorical columns that I describe below. The problem that we have to deal with here is to deal with the null values.¶

Data Preprocessing¶

Step 1: Encoding¶

I encode the data using the label encoder, which is hierarchal encoder. I have used this encoder because it does not increase the dimensionality of the data.

In [43]:
loan_df_encoded = loan_df
In [44]:
le = LabelEncoder()
for column in loan_df[['emp_title', 'state', 'homeownership','verified_income',
                                                         'verification_income_joint','loan_purpose','application_type',
                                                         'grade', 'sub_grade', 'issue_month', 'loan_status',
                                                         'initial_listing_status','disbursement_method']]:
    loan_df_encoded[column] = le.fit_transform(loan_df[column])

Dealing with columns with missing values¶

loan_df_encoded.shape

knn imputation to fill the missing data¶

I used knn imputation here which applies the knn algorithm on the column and predicts the missing values. I used this method of prediction because using other imputation might have skewed the data. KNN approximates the values by the points that are closest to them.

In [48]:
# import the KNNimputer class
from sklearn.impute import KNNImputer
# create an object for KNNImputer
imputer = KNNImputer(n_neighbors=2)
In [49]:
imputer.fit(loan_df_encoded)
loan_df_encoded[:] = imputer.transform(loan_df_encoded)

Scaling the data with a robust scaler¶

The data has many outliers so I chose the robust scaler since it uses the Interquartile range to normalize the data. Data normalization was needed here to give all the attributes the same influence for prediction

In [85]:
#Residuals vs Leverage

from numpy import sqrt

def one_line(x):
    return sqrt((1 * len(model.params) * (1 - x)) / x)

def point_five_line(x):
    return sqrt((0.5 * len(model.params) * (1 - x)) / x)
    
    
    
def show_cooks_distance_lines(tx,inc,color,label):
    plt.plot(inc,tx(inc), label=label,color=color, ls='--')
    
        

sns.regplot(model.get_influence().hat_matrix_diag, 
           model.get_influence().resid_studentized_internal, 
            scatter=True, 
            ci=False, 
            lowess=True,
            line_kws={'color': 'blue', 'lw': 1, 'alpha': 0.8},
          scatter_kws={'facecolors':'none', 'edgecolors':'black'})

show_cooks_distance_lines(one_line,
                        np.linspace(.01,.14,100),
                          'red',
                          'Cooks Distance (D=1)' )

show_cooks_distance_lines(point_five_line,
                          np.linspace(.01,.14,100),
                          'black',
                          'Cooks Distance (D=0.5)')

plt.title('Residuals vs Leverage', fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Leverage', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Standardized Residuals', fontsize=15)
plt.legend()
Out[85]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fa06080fac0>

Leverage refers to the extent to which the coefficients in the regression model would change if a particular observation was removed from the datas, Standardized residuals refer to the standardized difference between a predicted value for an observation and the actual value of the observation.

In [87]:
def evaluate(model,X_train,X_test,Y_train,Y_test):
    
    model.fit(X_train,Y_train)
    predictions_train = model.predict(X_train)
    predictions_test = model.predict(X_test)
    
    errors_train = abs(predictions_train - Y_train)
    errors_test = abs(predictions_test - Y_test)
    
    mape_train = 100 * np.mean(errors_train / Y_train)
    mape_test = 100 * np.mean(errors_test / Y_test)
    
    accuracy_train = 100 - mape_train
    accuracy_test = 100 - mape_test
    print('Model Performance')
    print('Average Error(Train Data): {:0.4f} of int rate.'.format(np.mean(errors_train)))
    print('Average Error(Test Data): {:0.4f} of int rate.'.format(np.mean(errors_test)))
    
    print('Accuracy(Train Data) = {:0.2f}%.'.format(accuracy_train))
    print('Accuracy(Test Data) = {:0.2f}%.'.format(accuracy_test))
    
    print('Mape(Train Data): {:0.4f} of int rate'.format(mape_train))
    print('Mape(Test Data): {:0.4f} of int rate'.format(mape_test))
    
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,10))
    plt.scatter(predictions_train,(predictions_train - Y_train),c='g',s=40,alpha=0.5)
    plt.scatter(predictions_test,(predictions_test - Y_test),c='b',s=40,alpha=0.5)
    plt.hlines(y=0,xmin=0,xmax=30)
    plt.title('residual plot blue(test) and green(train)data')
    plt.ylabel('residuals')
    return accuracy_train,accuracy_test
